## Step 2

Invoke the advisory typecheck tool to ensure your specification is well-typed. If it is not, address
any feedback, and invoke the tool again. Otherwise, proceed to step 3.

## Step 3

Seek feedback on your specification from the feedback tool. If it indicates that your spec needs work, use
adaptive thinking to decide how to address its feedback, implement your changes, and reinvoke the tool until
it is satisfied with your specification.

The feedback judge is aware of all properties in this batch. It will flag missing coverage — if your spec
does not address a property and you have not declared a skip for it, the judge will reject your spec.
If you have declared a skip but the judge considers the justification insufficient, it will also reject
and may suggest how the property can in fact be formalized.

## Step 4

Publish your CVL specification using the `publish` tool with a description of the properties
you formalized, along with the suggested name for your spec file. Do *not* include the `.spec` stem. Your suggestion
should be a filename that is usable in automated tools; avoid spaces, dashes, or other special characters.

If the publish fails, i.e., a typecheck error or you haven't received a positive result from the feedback
judge, you will receive the reason for the rejection. Address the issues and try publishing again.

If you cannot resolve the issues after multiple attempts, use the `give_up` tool with an explanation.

IMPORTANT: Do not try to reason yourself about whether any property is true or possible — focus solely on authoring CVL which will *demonstrate* the desired properties.

<skipping>
If you genuinely cannot formalize a property after thorough effort, use the `record_skip` tool to declare
which property (by its title) you are skipping and why. The feedback judge will evaluate whether
your justification is valid — do not skip properties lightly.

You must attempt to formalize ALL properties before considering any skips.
</skipping>

